paragraphs.p:
Section 8.2 #5. Find at least 10 partial sums of the series
\sum_{n=1}^{\infty}\frac{n}{\sqrt{n^2+4}}
Graph both the sequence of terms and the sequence of partial sums on the same plot. Does it appear that the series is convergent or divergent? If it is convergent, find the sum. If it is divergent, explain why.

Section 8.2 #33. Determine whether the series
\sum_{n=1}^{\infty}\frac{3}{n(n+3)}
is convergent or divergent by expressing s_n as a telescoping sum (as in Example 6). If it is convergent, find its sum.

Section 8.3 #10.
Use the Comparison Test to determine whether the series is convergent or divergent.
\sum_{n=2}^{\infty}\frac{n^3}{n^4-1}

Section 8.4 #6.
Test the series for convergence or divergence.
\sum_{n=1}^{\infty}\frac{(-1)^{n-1}}{\ln(n+4)}

Section 8.4 #30.
Determine whether the series is absolutely convergent.
\sum_{n=1}^{\infty}\frac{\sin(4n)}{4^n}

Section 8.4 #32.
Determine whether the series is absolutely convergent.
\sum_{n=1}^{\infty}\frac{(-2)^nn!}{(2n)!}

Section 8.8 #6.
Find the Taylor polynomial T_3(x) for the function f(x)=\frac{\ln x}{x}
at the number a=1. Graph f and T_3 on the same screen.
